  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Response to COVID-19 in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On 31 December 2019, a cluster of pneumonia of unknown etiology was reported in Wuhan City, Hubei Province of China. On 30 January WHO declared the outbreak of novel Coronavirus a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.  Particularly, WHO raises alert of low and middle income country and the preparedness of potential outbreaks.  As of 26 February 2020, a total of 82,297 cases of COVID-19 have been confirmed and 2,805 fatalities have been reported across 47 countries. There are 141 cases in Iran which shares a large border with Afghanistan. On 24 February Afghanistan&#x2019;s Ministry of Public Health (MoPH) reported one suspected case had been confirmed in the western province of Hirat. The person had recently travelled from Qom, the Islamic Republic of Iran. The  MoPH has declared a state of emergency in Hirat, closed It is reported that all schools are closed and  and banned public gatherings banned  until further notice. As of 27 February, MoPH has now reported 10 suspected cases (seven in Hirat, two in Ghor and one in Hilmand).


Globally, case fatality rate of COVID-19 stands at 2.4%.  However, in Very Low Income Countries like Afghanistan where the existing health system is weak, the emergence COVID-19 will overwhelm health provision and will likely cause more fatlaity than the global case fatality rate.


There are nine priority areas that WHO plans to cover on the overall COVID-19 response.  Under the AHF Reserve Allocation, the following six thematic areas are covered


1) Improved capacity at international points of entry - 12 entry points (Hamed Karzai International Airport, Balkh Airport, Kandahar airport, Ayratan border, Turkham, Sherkhan Border, Islam Qala, Spen Boldak, Badakhshan borders, Aqina border in Faryab, and Farah)
2) Strengthened surveillance and reporting systems
3) Improved case management
4) Enhanced national and regional health facilities infection prevention and control in Afghan Japan Hospital and 5 regional facilites in high prioroty areas.
5) Improved risk communication and community engagement
6) Technical assistance</narrative>
  </description>
